{
  "Energy flows through ecosystems in:": "",
  "Random directions with no pattern": "",
  "Cycles that repeat endlessly": "",
  "A one-way direction, from the sun through producers to consumers, eventually lost as heat": "",
  "Reverse, from consumers to producers": "",
  "Unlike matter which cycles, energy flows in one direction through ecosystems. Solar energy is captured by producers, transferred to consumers, and eventually lost as heat at each trophic level.": "",
  "Approximately what percentage of energy is transferred from one trophic level to the next?": "",
  "10% (the 10% rule)": "",
  "50% (the half-energy rule)": "",
  "100% (complete transfer efficiency)": "",
  "1% (the minimal transfer rule)": "",
  "The 10% rule states that approximately 10% of the energy at one trophic level is passed to the next. The remaining 90% is lost primarily as heat through cellular respiration and metabolic processes.": "",
  "Gross primary productivity (GPP) is:": "",
  "The total amount of energy (biomass) produced by photosynthesis in producers per unit area per unit time": "",
  "Energy lost as heat by decomposers": "",
  "Only the energy stored in animal tissues": "",
  "The total amount of energy consumed by all organisms": "",
  "Gross primary productivity is the total rate at which producers (plants, algae) convert solar energy into chemical energy through photosynthesis, before any energy is used for their own respiration.": "",
  "Net primary productivity (NPP) equals:": "",
  "GPP minus the energy producers use for their own respiration": "",
  "GPP + respiration": "",
  "Total ecosystem energy": "",
  "Only decomposer energy": "",
  "Net primary productivity (NPP = GPP - R) is the energy remaining after producers use some for their own cellular respiration. NPP represents the energy available to consumers in the ecosystem.": "",
  "The first law of thermodynamics states that energy:": "",
  "Always increases in amount": "",
  "Cannot be created or destroyed, only transformed from one form to another": "",
  "Can be created from nothing": "",
  "Can be destroyed completely": "",
  "The first law of thermodynamics (conservation of energy) states that energy cannot be created or destroyed. In ecosystems, solar energy is transformed into chemical energy by producers, then into kinetic energy and heat.": "",
  "The second law of thermodynamics explains why:": "",
  "Energy increases as it moves through food chains": "",
  "Ecosystems do not need energy inputs": "",
  "Every energy transfer results in some energy being lost as heat, making energy transfers less than 100% efficient": "",
  "Matter can be created from energy": "",
  "The second law of thermodynamics states that every energy transformation increases entropy (disorder). In ecosystems, this means usable energy decreases at each trophic level as heat is lost.": "",
  "If producers in an ecosystem capture 10,000 kcal of energy, approximately how much would be available to secondary consumers?": "",
  "10,000 kcal (all energy transfers perfectly)": "",
  "10 kcal (only 0.1% of energy transfers each step)": "",
  "100 kcal (10% of 10% = 1% of original)": "",
  "1,000 kcal (10% of the original producer energy)": "",
  "Applying the 10% rule: producers have 10,000 kcal, primary consumers get 1,000 kcal (10%), and secondary consumers get 100 kcal (10% of 1,000). This explains why food chains rarely exceed 4-5 levels.": "",
  "Ecological pyramids of energy are always upright because:": "",
  "Energy is lost as heat at each trophic level, so less energy is available at higher levels": "",
  "There are always more predators than prey": "",
  "Producers are always the smallest organisms": "",
  "Scientists design them to look that way": "",
  "Energy pyramids are always upright because the second law of thermodynamics guarantees that energy is lost as heat at each transfer, so each higher trophic level always has less total energy available.": "",
