  "Heat through cellular respiration at each trophic level": "",
  "Light energy radiated from bioluminescent organisms within the ecosystem": "",
  "Sound energy generated through animal communication and ecological interactions": "",
  "Chemical energy stored in waste products that are never broken down or recycled": "",
  "At each trophic level, organisms use most of the energy they consume for cellular respiration (metabolism, movement, maintaining body temperature), which releases energy as heat that dissipates into the environment.": "",
  "What is a trophic level?": "",
  "The maximum depth of water measured in a freshwater lake or reservoir ecosystem": "",
  "A feeding position in a food chain that describes an organism's relationship to the flow of energy in an ecosystem": "",
  "A classification of tropical climate zones based on average annual temperature ranges": "",
  "A government classification system used to rank species by their conservation priority": "",
  "A trophic level is each step in a food chain or food web where energy is transferred. Producers are the first level, primary consumers second, secondary consumers third, and so on.": "",
  "What is gross primary productivity (GPP)?": "",
  "The total rate of photosynthesis in an ecosystem, representing all energy fixed by producers before any is used for respiration": "",
  "The rate at which herbivore animals consume and digest plant material in an ecosystem": "",
  "The total energy stored in underground fossil fuel deposits within a geographic region": "",
  "The combined energy present in an ecosystem including both usable energy and waste heat": "",
  "Gross primary productivity is the total amount of energy captured through photosynthesis per unit area per unit time. It represents all carbon fixed by producers before subtracting respiratory losses.": "",
  "What is net primary productivity (NPP)?": "",
  "The energy remaining after producers subtract the energy used for their own respiration (NPP = GPP - R)": "",
  "The total energy produced by all organisms across every trophic level in the ecosystem": "",
  "The net financial profit generated from the commercial harvest of ecosystem resources": "",
  "The thermal energy lost as heat during metabolic processes at each trophic level": "",
  "Net primary productivity is the rate at which producers store energy as biomass after using some for their own metabolism. It represents the energy actually available to be consumed by herbivores.": "",
  "What is the 10% rule in ecology?": "",
  "A rule stating 10% of species go extinct each year": "",
  "A law requiring 10% of land to be protected": "",
  "A guideline for donating 10% of income to conservation": "",
  "The principle that only about 10% of the energy at one trophic level is transferred to the next trophic level": "",
  "The 10% rule is an ecological approximation stating that roughly 10% of energy at each trophic level is passed to the next level. The remaining 90% is used for metabolism and lost as heat.": "",
  "What is an energy pyramid?": "",
  "A large-scale food storage structure designed for preserving agricultural surplus harvests": "",
  "An ancient Egyptian historical structure that was originally powered by early solar panel technology": "",
  "A graphical representation showing the amount of energy available at each trophic level, always narrowing toward the top": "",
  "A pyramid-shaped industrial power plant designed to generate electricity from biomass fuels": "",
  "An energy pyramid (ecological pyramid of energy) shows the amount of energy at each trophic level. It is always upright because energy decreases at higher levels due to heat loss at each transfer.": "",
  "What is entropy?": "",
  "A standardized methodology used to assess and measure overall ecosystem health indicators": "",
  "The combined total of all forms of energy present throughout the entire known universe": "",
  "A measure of disorder or randomness in a system that increases with every energy transformation": "",
  "A particular category of energy source derived from nuclear or geothermal geological processes": "",
  "Entropy is a measure of disorder that always increases during energy transformations (second law of thermodynamics). In ecosystems, entropy explains why energy is progressively lost as unusable heat.": "",
  "What is assimilation efficiency?": "",
  "The speed at which organisms eat": "",
  "The rate of photosynthesis in plants": "",
  "The percentage of consumed food energy that an organism absorbs and uses rather than excreting as waste": "",
  "The percentage of sunlight reaching the ground": "",
  "Assimilation efficiency is the fraction of ingested food that an organism actually absorbs across its gut wall for use in metabolism and growth, versus what passes through as feces.": "",
  "What is ecological efficiency?": "",
  "The percentage of energy transferred from one trophic level to the next in a food chain": "",
  "The number of species in an ecosystem": "",
  "The speed at which ecosystems recover from disturbances": "",
  "The rate at which water flows through a river": "",
  "Ecological efficiency (also called food chain efficiency) is the percentage of energy at one trophic level that is incorporated into biomass at the next trophic level, typically averaging around 10%.": "",
  "What is standing crop biomass?": "",
  "Only the weight of crops in a farm field": "",
  "The total mass of living organisms present in an ecosystem or at a trophic level at a given time": "",
  "The weight of dead organisms on the ground": "",
  "The amount of sunlight hitting an area": "",
  "Standing crop biomass is the total amount of living biological material at a given trophic level or in an ecosystem at a particular moment in time, usually measured as dry mass per unit area.": "",
  "What is cellular respiration in the context of energy flow?": "",
  "The photosynthetic process by which green plants create food from sunlight and carbon dioxide": "",
  "The metabolic process that breaks down organic molecules to release energy (ATP), producing CO2 and H2O and releasing heat": "",
  "The biological decomposition of dead organic matter by bacteria and fungal microorganisms": "",
  "The physical act of breathing performed by animals to exchange gases with the atmosphere": "",
  "Cellular respiration is the process by which all living organisms convert organic molecules into ATP energy, releasing CO2, water, and heat. It accounts for the majority of energy loss at each trophic level.": "",
  "A farmer is deciding whether to raise cattle (secondary consumers) or grow soybeans (producers) on 100 acres of land. From an energy efficiency perspective, growing soybeans would feed more people because:": "",
  "Eating lower on the food chain is more energy-efficient since approximately 90% of energy is lost at each trophic level": "",
  "Soybeans taste significantly better than beef according to most consumer preference surveys": "",
  "Cattle actually produce more edible food per acre of farmland than any plant-based crop": "",
  "Soybeans require substantially more water and land inputs per calorie than raising cattle": "",
  "Due to the 10% rule, eating plants directly is roughly 10 times more energy-efficient than eating animals that consumed those plants. This is why plant-based diets have smaller ecological footprints.": "",
